West 35th Street, north side, west of 9th Ave., showing tenements. Through the center of this block will be cut a swath providing for the entrance causeway to the Lincoln Tunnel. This new thoroughfare will be known as Dyer Avenue and will be approximately midway between 9th and 10th Aves. The buildings to be demolished for same are in the foreground of the larger view, extending equidistant from the two low structures in the direct center. The smaller photo is taken from a point closer to 9th Ave. Note the two story frame building, No. 407, that adjoins the partially shown structure at the N.W. corner of the Avenue
View 1: August 30, 1934
P.L. Sperr
View 2: About 1928

(1)
West 35th Street, north side, between Ninth and Tenth Avenues, showing Dyer Avenue, the approach to the Lincoln Tunnel, under construction. The photographer is viewing northward and shows, tenements between 35th and 36th Streets already demolished. Shown thru this clearance are additional structures on the 36th to 37th Street block, that will soon follow. Those to the left will remain and form the westerly side of this vehicular approach. Note there the stained glass windows of St. Chiaras (St. Clare) Roman Catholic Church.

March 18, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same vicinity at a later date. The photographer here is viewing north eastward from the western side of the new Dyer Avenue and shows the McGraw-Hill Bldg. dominating the skyline. Note the concrete retaining wall already in place.

Dec. 1, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.
